96":"1596","Abt 1536":"about 1536","Burslem, Stoke-on-Trent district, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Burslem, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Danyell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (Galway): variant of   Daniel  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Daniel","meanings":["English, French, Spanish, Portuguese, German, Polish, Czech, Slovak, Romanian, Jewish, Assyrian/Chaldean, West Indian (mainly Haiti), and African (mainly Nigeria and Tanzania); Breton (rarely <b>Le Daniel</b>); Hungarian (<b>Dániel</b>): from the Biblical personal name <i>Daniel</i>, Syriac (Assyrian/Chaldean) <i>Dānīʾēl</i>, Hungarian <i>Dániel</i> (from Hebrew <i>Daniyyel</i> ‘God is my judge’), borne by a major prophet in the Bible. The chief factor influencing the popularity of the personal name (and hence the frequency of the surname) was undoubtedly the dramatic story in the Book of Daniel recounting the prophet's steadfast adherence to his religious faith despite pressure and persecution from the Mesopotamian kings in whose court he served: Nebuchadnezzar, Belshazzar, and Darius. The name was also borne by a 2nd-century Christian martyr and by a 9th-century hermit, the legend of whose lives were popular among Christians during the Middle Ages. Among Orthodox Christians in Eastern Europe the name was also popular as being that of a 4th-century Persian martyr, who was venerated in the Orthodox Church. In France, this surname is most common in Brittany.","Irish (Tipperary and Waterford): shortened form of   McDaniel  , which is actually a variant of   McDonnell  , from the Gaelic form of Irish <i>Donal</i> (equivalent to Scottish <i>Donald</i>), erroneously associated with the Biblical personal name <i>Daniel</i>. See also   O'Donnell  .","Americanized or Germanized form of Slovenian <b>Danijel</b>: from the Biblical personal name <i>Danijel</i> ‘Daniel’ (see 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Danyell was born about 1520, in Burslem, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs. Thomas Danyell."},"et":{"Abt 1520–":"umbes 1520–Surnud","1521–Female":"1521–Surnud","1536–1596":"1536–1596","1520–Male":"1520–Surnud","1536":"1536","Abt 1520":"umbes 1520","1521":"1521","1520":"1520","1596":"1596","Abt 1536":"umbes 1536","Burslem, Stoke-on-Trent district, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Burslem, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1520–":"noin 1520–Kuollut","1521–Female":"1521–Kuollut","1536–1596":"1536–1596","1520–Male":"1520–Kuollut","1536":"1536","Abt 1520":"noin 1520","1521":"1521","1520":"1520","1596":"1596","Abt 1536":"noin 1536","Burslem, Stoke-on-Trent district, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Burslem, Staffordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1520–":"environ 1520–Décédé","1521–Female":"1521–Décédée","1536–1596":"1536–1596","1520–Male":"1520–Décédé","1536":"1536","Abt 1520":"environ 1520","1521":"1521","1520":"1520","1596":"1596","Abt 1536":"environ 1536","Burslem, Stoke-on-Trent district, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Burslem, Staffordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Thomas Danyell est né environ 1520, à Burslem, Staffordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Mrs. Thomas Danyell."},"de":{"Abt 1520–":"um 1520–Verstorben","1521–Female":"1521–Verstorben","1536–1596":"1536–1596",